text: Induction of p16INK4a Transcription and of Cellular Senescence by Aclacinomycin-Derivatives and Cardiac Glycosides a Kiyoshi EGAWA,a Yosuke KURIHARA,a Tatsuya ITO,b Masahiko MATSUMOTO,b and Kiyoshi NOSE Department  of  Microbiology,  Showa  University  School  of  Pharmaceutical  Sciences,a 1–5–8  Hatanodai,  Shinagawa-ku, Tokyo 142–8555, Japan and Pharmaceutical Technology Laboratory, Chugai Pharmaceutical Co., Ltd.,b 1–135 Komakado, Gotemba, Shizuoka 412–8513, Japan. Received September 17, 2001; accepted December 24, 2001 The p16INK4a, also called CDKN2, and MST1, is a speciﬁc inhibitor of cyclin-dependent kinases CDK4 and CDK6, and a  putative  tumor  suppressor  whose  gene  is  often  deleted  in different  types  of  human  cancers.1—4) CDKs  have  critical roles  in  cell-cycle  progression  by  phosphorylating  the retinoblastoma  gene  product  (pRB),5,6) and  their  inhibitors play  important  roles  in  regulation  of  the  cell-cycle.  mRNA levels  of  p16INK4a are  elevated  in  senescent  human  ﬁbrob- lasts,7,8) and  forced  expression  of  p16INK4a induced  cellular senescence in immortalized ﬁbroblasts.9,10) These ﬁndings in- dicate  that  p16INK4a is  involved  in  cellular  senescence  in which cell growth is irreversibly arrested.

Expression  of  p16INK4a is  regulated  primarily  at  the  tran- scriptional  level,  the  signal  for  which  includes  the  Ras-Raf- MEK kinase cascade.11,12) The targets of this signaling to in- duce  p16INK4a have  recently  been  shown  to  be  transcription factors,  Ets1/Ets2,  that  bind  and  activate  the  p16INK4a pro- moter.13) The  Ets  family  of  transcription  factors  are  nega- tively  regulated  by  a  helix-loop-helix  protein  Id,14) and  in senescent  cells  the  level  of  Ets1  increased,  whereas  the  Id level was reciprocally decreased.13) Some chemicals such as sodium butyrate15) and N-acetylcysteine16) are reported to in- duce the p16INK4a gene. From the above ﬁndings, it could be expected  that  agents  that  activate  the  p16INK4a promoter would induce cellular senescence in immortalized cells, and are  potential  anti-tumor  agents.  We  previously  reported  a screening system that used the luciferase reporter gene under control of the transcriptional regulatory region of the p21Cip1 gene,  and  the  system  worked  to  identify  several  anti-tumor agents.17) In  the  present  communication,  we  extended  our previous  system  using  a  reporter  system  that  contained  a human p16INK4a promoter, and identiﬁed several active agents that induced cellular senescence. Cell  Lines Human  osteosarcoma  cells  (Saos-2)  were cultured in a-MEM supplemented with 10% heat-inactivated fetal  bovine  serum  under  a  humidiﬁed  atmosphere  of  95% air/5%  CO2.  The  reporter  that  contained  the  human  p16  59- * To whom correspondence should be addressed.

Stable  transformants  of  Saos-2  cells  that  contain  the  luciferase  reporter  gene  under  the  control  of  the human p16INK4a transcriptional regulatory region were established, and were used to identify growth-inhibiting substances from culture broths of actinomycetes and extracts of plants. Among the active substances so far iden- tiﬁed were an aclacinomycin-derivative, cenerubin B, and a cardiac glycoside, periplocin. These substances in- hibited growth of normal human ﬁbroblasts, and induced senescent phenotypes including a ﬂattened morphol- ogy and increased acidic bb-galactosidase activity, although the activities of their derivatives to induce p16CDKN2 and bb-galactosidase did not coincided with each other. These results suggest that the reporter system using the p16CDKN2 transcriptional regulatory region is a useful means for screening growth inhibiting substances that are potential anti-tumor agents. One  of  the  clones,  #13,  that  stably  harbored  the  re- porter and responded well to n-butyrate was used for further studies. The p21-inducing activity was measured as  described  previously  using  a  stable  transformant,  clone #22.17) Luciferase  Assay Cells  were  plated  into  96-well  tissue culture plates (Falcon) at a density of 33103 cells/well, and treated with chemicals 16 h later. Cells were incubated for an additional 48 h, and harvested for determination of luciferase activity.  Assay  was  carried  out  using  a  kit  provided  by Promega  Corp.  (Madison,  WI)  following  the  manufacturer’s manual. AP-1/luciferase that contained seven TRE was pur- chased from Promega. SA  bb-Galactosidase  Assay TIG-7  cells  were  ﬁxed  in 2% formaldehyde and were stained in a solution as described previously.18) Blue-stained  positive  and  negative  cells  were counted under a microscope.

Test  Samples  and  Preparation  of  Extracts Fungi  and actinomycetes isolated from soil samples were cultivated for 5 d  at  27 °C  in  a  nutrient  medium  (glucose  2%,  starch  2%, soy  bean  meal  1%,  NaCl  0.3%,  dry  bouillon  0.1%,  CaCO3 0.3%). To an aliquot of whole broth three volumes of ethanol were added and the mixture was shaken. After centrifugation, the  upper  phase  was  concentrated  under  vacuum  and  ex- tracted with ethyl acetate. Dried  plant  materials  were  pulverized  with  a  spice  mill. Approximately 10 g of the pulverized plant parts was allowed to  stand  in  50 ml  of  75%  aqueous  ethanol  for  24 h  at  room temperature. Extracts of interest were separated by silica gel chromatography using a guide to identify the active material. Cinerubin  B19) and  periplocin20) were  isolated  and  puriﬁed from  the  culture  broth  of  an  actinomycete,  strain  No.  I-60, © 2002 Pharmaceutical Society of Japan and  the  root  bark  of  Periploca  sepium BUNGE,  (Asclepi- adaceae), which is called “Hokugokahi” in Japanese, respec- tively. Bufotalin and gincenoside Rgi and Rbi were purchasd from  Wako  Pure  Chemical  Industries  Ltd.  (Tokyo),  and digoxin, digitoxin and digitoxigenin were from Tokyo Kasei Kogyo  Co.,  Ltd.  (Tokyo).  The  other  cardiac  glycosides  (bu- falin, proscillaridin A, oleandrin, lanatoside C, convallatoxin, ouabain, gitoxin), aclacinomycin A, daunorubicin and doxo- rubicin were products of the Sigma Chemical Co. (St. Louis, MO, U.S.A.).

Activation of p16/Reporter by an Anthracycline-Deriv- ative,  Cinerubin  B,  and  a  Cardiac  Glycoside,  Periplocin From  the  screening  of  about  1000  plant  extracts  and  broths of fungi or actinomycetes, we identiﬁed one active substance in each extract, respectively. Each active substance was puri- ﬁed,  and  determination  of  its  chemical  structure  revealed periplocin20) from  75%  ethanol  extracts  of  P.  sepium,  and cinerubin B (1-hydroxy-aclacinomycin B)19) from the culture broth of an actinomycetes, strain No. I-60. As  shown  in  Fig.  1,  cinerubin  B  is  a  potent  inducer  of p16/reporter  at  concentrations  of  40  to  200 ng/ml,  and  also activated p21/luciferase activity. At higher doses, it was toxic to  the  cells,  and  hence  luciferase  activity  was  decreased. Other  anthracycline-derivatives,  doxorubicin,  daunorubicin, and  aclacinomycin  A,  were  not  as  potent  as  cinerubin  B  in inducing p16 promoter (Fig. 1). These antibiotics are known to have anti-tumor activity and are used clinically,21) and also induce  differentiation  of  leukemia  cells.22,23) They  appear  to be inhibitors of topoisomerase II,24) but the mode of actions of cinerubin B has not yet been characterized. From the ﬁnd- ings shown in Fig. 1, it can be expected that cinerubin B has a unique biological action among anthracycline-derivatives.

Saos-2 stable transformants, #13 (ﬁlled bars) and #22 (open bars), were used to measure p16/ and p21/luciferase activity, respectively. Cells were treated with cinerubin B, acla- cinomycin A, daunorubicin, or doxorubicin at 1.6 ng/ml (1), 8 ng/ml (2), 40 ng/ml (3), 200 ng/ml (4) or 1 mg/ml (5) for 48 h. Relative luciferase activity based on the untreated con- trol was calculated. The values are the means of three independent experiments. Induction of p16/ and p21/Luciferase Activity by Aclacinomycin-Derivatives

Another  active  substance  isolated  from  plant  extracts, periplocin, activated p16/luciferase activity at 1 to 100 mg/ml (Fig. 2a). As periplocin is a cardiac glycoside, the p16-induc- ing  activity  was  examined  using  other  cardiac  glycosides. Figure 2a and b show that periplocin as well as bufotalin, gi- toxin, digitoxin, and digitoxigenin also strongly induced p16 promoter  activity  at  concentrations  as  low  as  0.1—1 mg/ml. These  agents,  however,  did  not  induce  the  p21/WAF1  pro- moter (Fig. 2b) that was activated by histone deacetylase in- hibitor, n-butyrate, and actinomycin D.17) These cardiac gly- cosides  are  an  inhibitor  of  Na1/K1-ATPase,25) and  induce differentiation  of  leukemia  cells26,27) and  melanoma  cells.27) The relationship between the structure of cardiac glycosides and  the  differentiation-inducing  activity  has  not  been  exten- sively  determined,  but  in  the  case  of  melanoma  differentia- tion, ouabain was more potent than bufalin. In p16-induction, these  two  agents  had  similar  activity  (Fig.  2a, b),  and  the mechanisms  underlying  these  two  processes  may  be  differ- ent.  Digitalis  was  proposed  to  be  an  anticancer  agent.29) Periplocin  and  bufotalin  are  thus  expected  to  be  potential chemotherapeutic agents against cancer.

To  examine  the  speciﬁcity  of  induction,  the  AP-1/lu- ciferase that is controlled by the TPA-responsive element was used  as  a  reporter  at  optimal  doses  to  induce  p21/luciferase reporter. The results shown in Fig. 3 suggest that periplocin and  bufotalin  strongly  activated  expression  of  AP-1/lu- ciferase but cenerubin B did not. The latter induced p21/lu- ciferase but the former did not (Figs.1, 2). These characteris- tics suggest that the mode of action of these agents is differ- ent, even though they induced p16/luciferase expression. Induction  of  Senescent  Phenotypes p16  expression  is known  to  be  elevated  during  cellular  senescence  of  normal human  ﬁbroblasts,9,10) but  levels  of  mRNA  of  p16  were  not signiﬁcantly  increased  in  TIG-7  cells  treated  with  either periplocin or cinerubin B as revealed from Northern blotting (a) Cells of clone #13 were treated for 48 h with the indicated agents at 10 ng/ml (1), 100 ng/ml (2), 1 mg/ml (3), 10 mg/ml (4) or 100 mg/ml (5). (b) Clone #22 cells were treated for 48 h with the indicated agents at 10 ng/ml (1), 100 ng/ml (2), 1 mg/ml (3), or 10 mg/ml (4). Relative luciferase activity based on the untreated control was calculated. The values are the means of three independent experiments. Induction of p16/ and p21/Luciferase Activity by Cardiac Glycosides

Cells of clone #13 were either untreated (1), or treated with 200 ng/ml cinerubin B (2), 1 mg/ml aclacinomycin A (3), 40 ng/ml bufotalin (4) or 200 ng/ml periplocin (5) in the ab- sence (ﬁlled bars) or presence (open bars) of 10 mM SB203580 (a) or PD98059 (b) for 48 h. Luciferase activity was measured, and the values are the means of three independent ex- periments. (data  not  shown).  The  cells  treated  with  these  agents,  how- ever,  showed  a  ﬂattened  morphology  that  is  associated  with senescent  cells.  As  a  marker  of  senescence,  expression  of acidic  b-galactosidase  activity  (SA-Gal)  was  examined  in TIG-7  cells  treated  with  cardiac  glycosides  and  aclacino- mycin-derivatives (Fig. 4). Periplocin, bufotalin, and cineru- bin  B  that  were  potent  inducers  of  p16/luciferase  increased the  fractions  of  SA-Gal-positive  cells.  Induction  of  this senescent  phenotypes  suggested  that  these  chemicals  act  as anti-tumor agents by inducing cellular senescence. Activities to  induce  p16/  or  p21/luciferase  were,  however,  not  directly related: aclacinomycin A did not activate p16/reporter but in- duced  induced  senescence-like  phenotypes,  whereas  oubain was  a  potent  inducer  of  p16/reporter  but  failed  to  induce senescent  phenotypes  (Fig.  1  and  Fig.  4).  Even  though  p16 gene  expression  is  critical  for  cellular  senescence,7  —10) the mechanism  underlying  the  reporter-activation  by  drugs  may be different from senescent processes.

Effect of MAP Kinase Inhibitors on p16-Induction In the case of the induction of p21 by actinomycin D or tricho- statin,  an  inhibitor  of  stress-activated  protein  kinase  p38 (SB203580)  suppressed  the  induction.  The  signaling  path- ways to induce p16/luciferase were estimated by the addition of speciﬁc inhibitors. The results shown in Fig. 5 suggest that SB203580  signiﬁcantly  inhibited  the  induction  caused  by cinerubin B or aclacinomycin A, but did not signiﬁcantly af- fect the induction by cardiac glycosides. The MAP kinase in- hibitor, PD98059 did not affect the induction by either cate- gory of agents. Effect of Kinase Inhibitors on p16-Induction Induction of AP-1/Luciferase Activity rivatives activate signaling pathways that contain stress-acti- vated  protein  kinases,  but  cardiac  glycosides  work  through distinct  pathways.  Activated  ras  is  known  to  induce  senes- cence  and  p16  in  normal  ﬁbroblasts,11) but  the  MAP  kinase cascade  that  is  downstream  of  ras  did  not  seem  to  be  in- volved  in  p16  induction  by  cardiac  glycosides  or  anthracy- clins  (Fig.  5).  These  results  indicate  that  senescent  pheno- types induced by these chemicals are caused by different sig- nals from the normal senescent process.

The  real  targets  of  transcriptional  regulators  of  the  p16 gene that respond to these agents are unclear at present, but our preliminary results suggest that a 2167 bp upstream re- gion of the human p16 gene was sufﬁcient to drive the induc- tion of the luciferase reporter (data not shown). Whatever the mechanism,  the  assay  system  described  in  this  manuscript will be useful for large-scale screening of potential antitumor agents.
